'''Bhagawan Koirala''' ([[Nepali language|Nepali]]: भगवान कोइराला) [[Doctor of Medicine|MD]], [[American College of Cardiology|FACC]] (July 24, 1960) is a [[cardiothoracic surgery|
Cardiothoracic surgeon]], [[professor]] and [[Social worker]].<ref name="Bio">{{cite web|url=http://www.sgnhc.org.np/biodata/bhagwan-koirala.htm|title=Bhagwan Koirala bio|accessdate=2012-12-28|publisher=SGNHC.org.np}}</ref> He is best known for pioneering [[Open-heart surgery]] in [[Nepal]], and for starting an operational cardiac care for the public.<ref name="BK Intr."/>

He started a ''"Poor Patients Relief"'' program in 2003, with the support of the [[Government of Nepal]], which focuses on providing free [[Heart|Cardiac care]] for children, elderly and needy.<ref name="VideoChautari">{{cite web|url=http://videochautari.com/videos/398/merojindagi-merobiswas-prof-dr-bhagawan-koirala-2009-11-27|title= Dr. Koirala being interviews in a National TV|accessdate=2012-12-28|publisher=VideoChautari.com}}</ref>

==Education and background==
Koirala completed his schooling from his hometown of Palpa, where he earned his [[School Leaving Certificate (Nepal)|SLC]] at the young age of 13. He later earned his Certificate in General Medicine from [[Kathmandu]]. The interest for a career in medicine took him to [[Kharkiv]], [[Ukraine]], where he graduated from [[Kharkiv National Medical University|Kharkiv Medical Institute]] in 1989. He later explained in an interview that he credits his lecturer for encouraging him to earn a career in medicine, specially in the area of Cardiac surgery.

He [[Postgraduate education|post-graduated]] from [[National Institute of Cardiovascular Diseases]], [[Dhaka University]], in 1994, and later completed an unaccredited [[United States Medical Licensing Examination]] (Step I) in 1996 and (Step II and III) in 2000.<ref name="Bio"/><ref name="VideoChautari"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nepalitimes.com.np/issue/2003/08/22/NepaliSociety/3815#.UNweqnee2gt|title=Bhagawan Koirala in the making|accessdate=2012-12-28|publisher=NepaliTimes.com}}</ref>

===Residency and trainings===
He started his [[Residency (medicine)|residency]] from a government institution of Nepal, ''T.U. Casualty and Surgery'', in 1989, and got promoted to [[Senior house officer]] in ''[[Tribhuvan University|T.U.]] Department of Surgery'' in 1990. It was followed by the fellowships in the internationally recognized institutions; first as a resident (Cardiothoracic) in [[Dhaka University]] in 1991, and later as a resident (surgery) and [[Fellowship (medicine)|Clinical Fellow]] (Cardiac Surgery) in [[Baystate Medical Center]] of [[Massachusetts]] in 1998 and 1999 respectively.

He also completed his tenure as a Clinical Fellow (Cardiac surgery) in [[The Hospital for Sick Children]] of [[Toronto]] in
2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jtcs.ctsnetjournals.org/cgi/content/full/121/4/782|title=Pediatric Heart Transplant in Toronto 2000|accessdate=2012-12-28|publisher=CTSNetJournals.org}}</ref>

==Career==
<!---This section needs expansion-->
Koirala, specializing in [[Hybrid cardiac surgery#Pediatric cardiac surgery|pediatric cardiac surgery]], started his career from TU Teaching Hospital. He was the Executive Director and Chief of Cardiac Surgery of Shahid Gangalal National Heart Center between 2001 AND 2009.He is currently the Executive Director of TU Teaching Hospital.<ref name="Bio" /><ref name="SGNHC">{{cite web|url=
http://www.sgnhc.org.np/biodata/bhagwan-koirala.htm|title=Koirala's credentials|accessdate=2012-12-28|publisher=SGNHC.org.np}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctsnet.org/home/bkoirala|title=Dr. Koirala's Bio|accessdate=2012-12-28|publisher=CTSNet.org}}</ref> also known for being  a [[Philanthropy|philanthropic organization]]. He is also involved with different national and international projects and campaigns to ensure funds and charity for needy patients.<ref name="BK Intr.">{{cite web|url=http://lookandgaze.blogspot.com/2008/07/interview-with-dr-bhagawan-koirala.html|title=Koirala being interviewed by ''Reader's Club of Nepal''|accessdate=2012-12-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=hospital.http://www.sgnhc.org.np/anual_report_2007/full_book.pdf|title=Sahid Gangalal Hospital's Annual Report (2007|accessdate=2012-12-28|publisher=SGNHC.org.np)}}</ref>

He has performed over 10,000 heart operations, personally or directly supervised, from 2001 to 2012. Being one of the senior-most surgeon and capable administrator, he was appointed the [[Director (education)|Director]] of [[Tribhuvan University|T.U.]] Teaching Hospital (TUTH), where he first started his career, in November 2012.<ref name="TUTH" >{{cite web|url=http://www.teachinghospital.org.np/g.html|title=T.U. Teaching Hospital Payroll|accessdate=2012-12-28|publisher=Teaching Hospital of Nepal}}</ref>

